          "body": "Deuteronomy 26:1-11 is the most elaborately specified worship instruction in the Pentateuch's law-code. What makes it unusual is not the offering itself — firstfruits appear elsewhere (Exod 23:19; Num 18:12-13) — but the **liturgical script** attached to it. The worshiper is not merely commanded to bring produce; he is commanded to **say something**. The 'wandering Aramean' creed (26:5-9) is the oldest confessional formula in the Hebrew Bible; it is what Gerhard von Rad called the 'small historical credo.' The content moves from patriarchal origins (the Aramean ancestor — Jacob, who sojourned in Aram Naharaim and whose mother was Aramean, Gen 24-25) through the Egyptian sojourn, bondage, cry, divine hearing, miraculous deliverance, and land possession. The entire arc of redemption is rehearsed before a single basket is placed on the altar. Worship in this chapter is not spontaneous emotion — it is historically formed gratitude. The worshiper knows why he rejoices because he has rehearsed what God did to make rejoicing rational."
