          "title": "The covenant exchange — mutual declaration and covenantal identity",
          "body": "Verses 17-19 are the chapter's — and in many ways the entire law-code's — climax. The Hebrew of these verses is unique in the Old Testament: the verb form (*he'emarta* / *he'emirekha*) used for 'you have declared' and 'the LORD has declared' is the Hiphil causative of *aman*, related to *emunah* (faithfulness) and *amen*. It means something like 'to cause someone to affirm, to call someone out in commitment.' Scholars (Peter Craigie, *NICOT Deuteronomy*; J. G. McConville, *Apollos Deuteronomy*) recognize this as covenant-renewal language: Israel formally confesses Yahweh as God and pledges covenant loyalty (walk, keep, listen, 26:17); Yahweh formally confesses Israel as His *segullah* (treasured possession) and pledges covenant status (26:18-19). The exchange is symmetrical and mutual — not identical, for Yahweh remains sovereign and Israel remains creature, but genuinely bilateral. The covenant is not merely Yahweh's proclamation over a passive Israel; it is a relationship of mutual commitment. The eschatological horizon at 26:19 — 'set you high above all nations for praise, fame, and honor' — opens into the prophetic vision of Israel as the vehicle of Yahweh's glory before all peoples, fulfilled ultimately in the church as God's *segullah* (1 Pet 2:9) and in the new creation where the nations walk by the light of the Lamb (Rev 21:24)."
